post_text:
We are excited to announce that starting Monday (9/14), breakfast AND lunch will be provided to ALL students, both in-person and virtual, at NO COST! Virtual students (Classroom Connect AND eCollier Academy) may pick up NO COST grab and go meals at their closest CCPS school (no matter the grade level) during the following times:

- High Schools: 7:30am - 8:30am
- Elementary Schools: 8:30am - 9:00am
- Middle Schools: 9:30am - 10:00am

Students do not need to be present to pick up meals. Unless CCPS receives a federal extension, this program is scheduled to end December 31, 2020. bit.ly/33hvF6F

post_text:
UPDATE: Fall Athletic Events

We are pleased to announce that the Florida Department of Health-Collier has approved the ability to have limited spectator attendance at home athletic competitions. Each CCPS student-athlete, cheerleader, and band member will be permitted to invite 2 members of their household to attend each HOME event in which they are participating. This pertains to high school football, volleyball, and cross-country held on CCPS campuses only (home games only). Visiting teams will NOT be permitted spectators.

Spectators will be subject to health/safety guidelines, including using REQUIRED face coverings and practicing social distancing using pre-identified, marked bleacher seats which will allow for each participant's 2 household guests to sit together, but remain 6 feet apart from other spectators. Open-chin triangle bandanas and face coverings containing valves/vents, mesh material, lace, holes, or other largely porous materials are NOT acceptable.

Click on the link for additional information bit.ly/3hVsrvW #CCPSFamily

The countdown has officially begun! 5️⃣ days until school starts! Today's reminder: If your student is attending school on campus, face coverings are required on buses and school campuses beginning on the first day (8/31). CCPS face coverings and safety glasses (highly recommended) will be distributed on the first day of school to provide each student with additional supplies. If you would like to receive these supplies ahead of the first day, please contact your child’s school.

Note: Bandanas and masks with valves are not acceptable face coverings.

Visit collierschools.com/reopening for health guidelines and other important resources for returning to school.

post_text:
T.S. LAURA UPDATE #1 - CCPS is actively monitoring Tropical Storm Laura very closely. Current projected path has Collier County in cone of concern, with storm effects expected as early as Sunday evening and into Monday/Tuesday.

All school-based activities, such as athletic practices/conditioning and laptop pick-up events, scheduled for Monday, August 24th, are CANCELED.

CCPS will continue to monitor the storm's path and collaborate with the Collier County Bureau of Emergency Management for the latest information regarding storm impacts and any potential shelter openings.

We will continue to utilize all of our communication channels for updates throughout this weather situation.

UPDATE: School Board Referendum passes with 80% approval! THANK YOU!

“We are thrilled to see Collier County passed the tax-neutral referendum. Voters overwhelmingly said ‘yes’ to helping ensure our students are college, career, and life ready. This flexibility will help maintain the programs and staff which make CCPS a high-performing school district.” –Dr. Kamela Patton
________________
Heading out to vote today? Remember the CCPS Referendum as you complete your ballot. For more information, please visit www.collierschools.com/referendum. Have a great day!

post_text: During COVID-19 we realize that many in our CCPS family may be struggling to pay the bills or make rent or mortgage payments on time. If you or someone you know is experiencing homelessness or at risk of being homeless, we encourage you to reach out to our CCPS McKinney-Vento Homeless Education Liaison for assistance at kafleh@collierschools.com or 239-377-0544. You may also visit the CCPS homeless education page on our website at www.collierschools.com/homeless for brochures and information on the educational rights of students experiencing homelessness and a comprehensive list and links to valuable resources. #CCPSFamily

Put your child on a path toward success! School starts August 31 and registration is open for all incoming kindergartners or any child who is new to the District. For convenience and safety, the process is completely online at http://www.collierschools.com/registration. You may call (239) 377-0547 with questions. Registration Tips:
1) Ensure you upload BOTH pages of the physical with the parent section completed and signed.
2) Ensure your physical is dated within 12 months of the first day of school.
3) Don't forget to sign and submit!

post_text:
QUESTION: When will face coverings/safety glasses measures be removed?

ANSWER: Stephanie Vick, Administrator, Florida Department of Health-Collier (FLDOH-Collier), provided the following information (as of July 14, 2020):

Once there is a positivity rate less than 10% and consistently dropping for a period of at least two weeks, then protective measures may be incrementally reduced. Masks would be the last protective measure to be made optional. Proper and frequent handwashing will stay

Our goal, over time and in consultation with the FLDOH-Collier, would be to loosen protective measures, as appropriate, in schools. At the start of the school year, however, we will be following the advisement of local healthcare experts to ensure a safe and healthy environment for students and staff.

Click here to see more Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) and answers to guide your #CCPSfamily in Moving Forward:
https://www.collierschools.com/reopening/faq#ecollier

“We have membranes in our eyes, in our nose, in our mouth, and this is the method of transmission. This is why using both mask and eyewear provides the highest level of safety.” -Dr. David Lindner, Medical Director of the Naples Community Hospital COVID-19 Response Team, discussing how to reduce the COVID-19 infection rate within enclosed spaces, like classrooms.

Source: July 15, 2020 Collier County Public Schools "Moving Forward" news conference.

Click here to read the guide for our Moving Forward plan:
https://www.collierschools.com/reopening

post_text:
QUESTION: "If I choose eCollier Academy for my child, does he/she lose their parental choice/Out-of-Zone spot?"
ANSWER: Yes, by enrolling at eCollier Academy you will be withdrawing your child from the out-of-zone school. You are therefore forfeiting your parental choice/out-of-zone spot at the school. As a result, that spot may be provided to another student on the waiting list to attend the school. However, if you wish to return to the parental choice/out-of-zone school, you are encouraged to reactivate your application for parental choice/out-of-zone at any time. Priority will be given to eCollier Academy students requesting their return to the previously approved parental choice/out-of-zone school; contingent upon available space (subject to class size requirements and staffing levels).

Click the following link to see more Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) relating to the CCPS Moving Forward plan:
https://www.collierschools.com/reopening/faq

Click here to see the full Family Information Guide for reopening:
https://www.collierschools.com/reopening

For more information and access to the survey, visit www.collierschools.com/reopening. #CCPSFamily

Congratulations to the Benison Center - Collier's 2020 Commissioner's Business Recognition Award (CBRA) District Honoree! https://www.floridaeducationfoundation.org/cbra

The goal of the CBRAs is to recognize Florida’s business leaders and partners that have shown the most commitment in bringing positive change and implementing bold, innovative approaches to improve the academic performance of students in Florida’s education system and communities. These educational connections help Florida school districts gain a competitive edge in providing enhanced services to the students they serve. We thank the Benison Center for all that they do for our students, teachers, and community! #CCPSFamily

post_text:
Today the #CCPSFamily commemorates Juneteenth. It dates back to 1865 in Galveston, Texas, and Juneteenth has officially been recognized as a special observance in Florida since 1991.￼ The CCPS “Gear Up For The Next School Year” activities (collierschools.com/gearup) provide students (grades K-10) with engaging and meaningful learning in the areas of English Language Arts, math, science and social studies throughout the summer. The activities in social studies, for the week of June 15, have provided students an opportunity to learn about the complex history of the United States and how Juneteenth is honored and commemorated. Students can choose to engage in learning through short videos, examining primary sources, and to consider the meaning of liberation.

Click the following link to learn more about this significant time in U.S. history.
https://www.history.com/news/what-is-juneteenth

Today, National Merit Scholarship Corporation (NMSC) announced over 3,300 winners of National Merit Scholarships financed by U.S. colleges and universities. Officials of each sponsor college selected their scholarship winners from among the Finalists in the 2020 National Merit Scholarship Program who plan to attend their institution. These awards provide between $500 and $2,000 annually for up to four years of undergraduate study at the institution financing the scholarship. Congratulations to the following three CCPS students who will be receiving a National Merit Scholarship:

Nicholas R. Borowski, Gulf Coast High School
Antonia M. LoFranco, Barron Collier High School
Anna I. Mazzone, Gulf Coast High School

Each of these students will be heading to the University of Florida! #CCPSProud #CCPSSuccess

post_text:
“No act of kindness is ever wasted, and has a long-lasting effect.” - Sandra Lee Buxton, owner of Life in Naples magazine.

Sandra, along with other anonymous charitable donors from Facebook and The Arlington of Naples, helped provide Lely Elementary School’s (LES) 2020 fifth-grade class with a yearbook of long-lasting memories to take with them as they move on to the next phase of their educational journey. Due to financial difficulties, only 20 yearbooks were sold at LES before the community stepped in to help. “It was important for us to give our fifth graders something in a challenging year to feel good about,” shared third-grade teacher Pam Rivera. A sentiment Principal Tammy Brown echoed, “I think our students will be happy to have those tangible memories that the yearbook provides, it’s like one last hug.”

A big thank you goes out to the many donors, especially The Arlington, for such a special gift! #CCPSFamily

UPDATED - The final day of eLearns for seniors is May 15th and June 3rd for students in grades K-11.

Grades for fourth quarter do count. 4th quarter grades will be part of: course grades, academic transcripts, GPA for middle and high school students, and criteria for academic honor societies.

Please monitor that your student is routinely completing and submitting assignments.

Middle and high school parents and students may continue to monitor grades in the FOCUS gradebook.

Elementary, middle and high school report cards will be available electronically by June 11, 2020; a reminder on directions to access will be provided in a future update.

We are here to help. Please contact teachers and school administrators if you need additional supports to stay on pace in eLearns. You may also email eLearns@collierschools.com.

post_text:
Congratulations to Palmetto Ridge High School's Anthony Bonet! Anthony is the recipient of the Jostens Yearbook National Student of the Month Award for April 2020. This award goes to a deserving student who has shown exceptional skills in the area of tenacity and the ability to motivate others and/or communicate effectively with peers and people in authority.

Anthony Bonet was selected based on his exceptional leadership and commitment to the school yearbook and students. Anthony's adviser Jodi Topping states, “Anthony leads by example: do your best, do it on time every time, and never shy away from a challenge.”

Read more about Anthony on the Jostens Yearbook Avenue blog: https://blog.yearbookavenue.jostens.com/blog/recognition/april-2020-adviser-student-of-the-month/

We recognize that virtual learning is a new experience and that many families are also facing unprecedented circumstances with your own work routines and lives. It is incredibly important that you know we all support you in balancing eLearns with your current circumstances. If it feels like too much for you or your students, adjust to what is manageable, stay in contact with your child’s teacher(s) and we will work to support you. You are also always welcome to send questions or comments to eLearns@collierschools.com. We are a CCPS Family!

REMINDER! FRIDAY, APRIL 10 & MONDAY, APRIL 13 ARE NON-SCHOOL/NON-WORK DAYS
Teachers will not post assignments in Canvas for these days.

For families that would like to maintain the eLearns routine, however, there will be optional, non-graded, enrichment activities available at collierschools.com/eLearns to keep learning alive!

REMINDER! TEACHER "OFFICE HOURS"
All teachers have "office hours" posted on the Canvas homepage for their class or course. These are times daily when they are readily available to communicate with students and parents.

post_text:
As we continue to navigate these challenging times, Collier County Public Schools wants to share some updates on high school events and activities.

PROMS AND SENIOR GRAD BASH EVENTS
All high school Proms and senior Grad Bash (or similar) events have been CANCELED. Refunds for any monies paid will be provided after May 1st.

UNDERCLASS END-OF-YEAR AWARDS
Award ceremonies for underclassmen will be rescheduled to the fall. Schools will provide further information on rescheduled dates and times in August after the new school year begins.

GRADUATION AND SENIOR AWARDS
Collier County Public Schools will continue to review plans for High School Graduation/Commencement Ceremonies and Senior Award Ceremonies as new guidance is received from the Florida Department of Education and the Centers for Disease Control in regards to school re-openings.

Please continue to monitor our District website, www.collierschools.com, as it is updated regularly.

Today, let's recognize Immokalee High School's David Stehlin! After Stehlin received his Golden Apple from Champions For Learning back in February, principal Clara Calderon shared these sentiments, "Mr. Stehlin is one those instructional staff that you wish you could duplicate. He builds strong relationships with students while engaging them to think critically on past events and relate them to current topics.” Congratulations, Mr. Stehlin! #CCPSProud #GoldenAppleCollier

And don't forget to tune in to the Golden Apple Celebration this Sunday, April 5, at 7PM on NBC-2!

post_text:
Today, the Commissioner of the Florida Department of Education has directed all public schools in Florida to continue to be closed through May 1, 2020. Therefore, Collier County Public Schools campuses will remain CLOSED to all students from Monday, March 30th through Friday, May 1st. Additional school closures will be re-evaluated by the Florida Department of Education prior to May 1st, and any changes will be communicated as soon as available.

At this time, Collier County Public Schools will continue CCPS eLearns Teacher-Led Virtual Instruction through May 1st. Any further extension of online learning will be based on guidance received from the Florida Department of Education. Students should log in to Canvas daily to access coursework from teachers. Visit our CCPS eLearns website at www.collierschools.com/eLearns for Canvas access, as well as supplemental learning activities, daily/weekly schedule templates, and many other resources.

Thank you for your continued patience and flexibility while we navigate uncharted territory during these challenging times.

post_text: Meal distribution for all Collier County students began this week at 27 school sites. In total, CCPS provided more than 20,000 meals this week! We thank our Nutrition Services department and school administrators for all that they are doing to ensure our students continue to receive healthy meals while at home. If you have a child in need of breakfast or lunch each day, please visit any one of our 27 meal distribution sites Monday through Friday between 9am-1pm (per federal regulations, children 18 and under must be present to receive meals). Visit https://www.collierschools.com/Page/13751 for a list of locations/addresses and access to a searchable map. We greatly appreciate everyone’s efforts as we navigate through this uncertain time!

Today, direction was provided to Florida school districts that all public schools in Florida continue to be closed through April 15, 2020. Therefore, Collier County Public Schools will be CLOSED to all students from Monday, March 23rd through Wednesday, April 15th. Additional school closures will be re-evaluated in two weeks and any changes will be communicated as soon as available.

Additionally, the Governor has canceled ALL state assessments for students in Pre-K through grade 12.

Collier County Public Schools is ready to transition to virtual/online continuous learning for students. We will provide further details about our Continuous Learning Plan in an update later this week.

shared_text:
Collier County Sheriff's Office
March 12 at 3:52 PM ·

JUNIOR DEPUTY DAY AT THE FAIR SATURDAY, MARCH 14, CANCELED

As part of our continued commitment to sharing important and confirmed community information with you, we must share this important information from the Collier County Junior Deputies League:

Out of the abundance of caution, the Collier County Junior Deputy Board of Directors and the Collier County Sheriff's Office at the recommendation of Sheriff Rambosk and his command team, have canceled this year's Fair Day . We will be working on a plan to allow students affected by this to attend next year. Thank you for your understanding. Please stay safe and take every precaution to keep yourself and your family healthy. Regards, Junior Deputies

We recently welcomed the Districts for Impact to Collier where we were able to demonstrate the success of our data dialogues…

post_text:
It's remarkable what can happen when a community comes together to support our students. Meet Billy, an Extended Transition program student at Immokalee High School. Billy's dream was to become an entrepreneur. With the guidance and support from many community friends, Billy's Fresh Produce was born!

Billy, now successfully selling produce at local farmers' markets, was in need of a vehicle to transport his equipment and produce. Thanks to the Barnhardt family, Billy was able to acquire a van! But that's not all. On the Spot Printing in Immokalee offered to wrap Billy's vehicle for FREE! Billy had no clue, and today, the group came together to surprise Billy with the wrapped van. As you can see, he was awestruck! It's moments like these that make a difference in the world. Thanks to everyone who had a part in making Billy's dream come true! #CCPSFamily

post_text: If we realized our community was missing out on millions of dollars in funding, shouldn’t we act? Homes across the country will begin receiving invitations, in mid-March, to complete the 2020 Census. A complete count is directly tied to how $675 Billion in federal money is spent across the U.S. Those dollars fund grants for transportation, EDUCATION, healthcare, and other vitally important programs. In the year 2000, only 64% of Collier County residents took part in the Census. The return rate grew to 71% in the 2010 Census; however, that’s still 29% of our population which was not counted. We can do better! #CollierCensus2020

Today, Lely High School received a special visit from a famous astronaut - although we learned he’s much more than that! Dr. Story Musgrave told his story (no pun intended 😊) to the school’s science, history, and aeronautical students. From farmer to mechanic, trauma surgeon to US Marine, NASA astronaut to landscape designer, Dr. Musgrave’s experiences captivated the crowd. What makes him most proud...being a father! He hopes to one day visit space with his youngest daughter. And we hope to see him do it! Thanks for sharing, “Daddy Story!”

Fact: Dr. Musgrave is the only astronaut to fly aboard all five Space Shuttles!

shared_text:
Collier County Sheriff's Office
January 7 at 5:59 PM ·

Collier County Sheriff’s Office detectives today arrested a Gulf Coast High School student after an investigation determined he was responsible for a threat of violence to Pine Ridge Middle School made over social media.

The 15-year-old student is charged with written threats to kill or do bodily injury or conduct a mass shooting or an act of terrorism, which is a second-degree felony under Florida Statute 836.10.

Detectives said the student confessed to making the threat, but denied having any plans or intentions of harming anyone. He told detectives he was mad at his parents and just wanted to scare people.

School safety remains our top concern. If you see something of concern please don’t spread it, report it.

Call 911 or the Collier County Sheriff’s Office non-emergency number at 239-252-9300, or to remain anonymous and be eligible for a reward contact Crime Stoppers at 1-800-780-8477.

Collier County Sheriff's Office
December 20, 2019 at 2:16 PM ·

UPDATE:

Detectives have arrested Jose Alfredo Avila Pena, 50, of Naples, charging him with second-degree murder. The investigation determined that Pena and the victim had previously been in a domestic relationship.

ORIGINAL RELEASE:

Homicide Investigation In East Naples
The Collier County Sheriff’s Office is conducting a homicide investigation in East Naples.
The incident was reported at 8:29 p.m. and occurred outside on the grounds at Lely High School.
Detectives said the victim, who is an adult, was shot.
Detectives are actively seeking a suspect and say there doesn’t appear to be any danger to the public.
Deputies are also interviewing witnesses and collecting evidence.
While there is no threat to the safety of staff or students, CCSO will have an increased law enforcement presence on the campus Friday.
An investigation continues. Information will be released as it becomes available.

post_text: Congratulations to Karen Stelmacki, the District's Director of Exceptional Student Education and Student Support Services! She was recently honored as the 2019 Outstanding Administrator of the Year by the Florida Association of School Psychologists (FASP), and the board recognized her at its Special Board Meeting just this morning. It's fitting as Karen will be retiring in December after 29 years of service to the district! Good luck, Karen...we wish you well on your next adventure!
